<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="printing" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Printing</title>
    <sage>
        <input>
          print("Hello, World!")
        </input>
      </sage>
    
      <p>
        Sometimes we use <c>Print()</c> to display output and sometimes we do not. Other times we need to use multiple print statements.
      </p>
    
      <sage>
        <input>
          "Hello, World!"
        </input>
      </sage>
    
      <sage>
        <input>
          "Hello, "
          "World!"
        </input>
      </sage>
    
      <p>
        It looks like Sage is only showing the value of the last line of code. If we want to print both of these strings we will need two print statements.
      </p>
    
      <sage>
        <input>
          print("Hello, ")
          print("World!")
        </input>
      </sage>
    
      <p>
        Did you expect these words to be on the same line? Let's investigate what <c>Print()</c> does. We can look up the documentation for a function by using the <c>?</c> operator at the end of the function name.
      </p>
    
      <sage>
        <input>
          print?
        </input>
      </sage>
    
      <p>
        It turns out <c>Print()</c> adds a new line after printing. Lets get the output we want on a single line.
      </p>
    
      <sage>
        <input>
          print("Hello, ", "World!")
        </input>
      </sage>
    
      <sage>
        <input>
          print("Hello, " + "World!")
        </input>
      </sage>

      <p>
        We can also display mathematical notation
      </p>
      <sage>
        <input>
          show(sqrt(2) * log(3)) 
        </input>
      </sage>
</section>